The paper deals with modelling and analyzing a decentralized communication system, specifically a parallel interference channel, as a non-cooperative game. This involves concepts from information theory (cs.IT) such as spectral efficiency and power allocation, as well as game theory (cs.GT) in terms of analyzing the Nash equilibria. The paper also discusses the use of Monte-Carlo simulations (cs.MM) to validate the theoretical results. Additionally, the paper involves network communication (cs.NI) and signal processing (cs.SI) concepts in the context of the interference channel.
